define({"topics":[{"title":"Configuring allowed client types","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">You can define the types of clients that can connect to the Sametime server.<\/p>","href":"config_st_allowed_client_types.html","attributes":{"data-id":"config_st_allowed_client_types"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"config_st_allowed_client_types-d1909e2560","topics":[]},{"title":"Configuring the preferred login list","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">By default, persistent chat enables a user that is logged in to multiple clients to     receive instant messaging sessions across all clients concurrently. In an environment that does     not support persistent chat and where the <a class=\"xref\" href=\"st_adm_comm_singlelogintype_t.html\">single       login type<\/a> feature is disabled, Sametime uses a default login order to determine which     client type should receive the instant messaging session. A preferred login list allows you to     override the default order.<\/p>","href":"st_adm_comm_prefloginlist_t.html","attributes":{"data-id":"st_adm_comm_prefloginlist_t"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"st_adm_comm_prefloginlist_t-d1909e2579","topics":[]},{"title":"Configuring the single login type","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">The single login type mode means that only one login per user is allowed. When a client     attempts to log in to the Sametime server, the server checks if there are any existing logins of     the same user and disconnects them. Any client on the exclusion list is not disconnected, which     is useful for users who want to run multiple clients simultaneously. <\/p>","href":"st_adm_comm_singlelogintype_t.html","attributes":{"data-id":"st_adm_comm_singlelogintype_t"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"st_adm_comm_singlelogintype_t-d1909e2601","topics":[]},{"title":"Sametime Client IDs","href":"new_client_ids.html","attributes":{"data-id":"new_client_ids"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"new_client_ids-d1909e2620","topics":[]}]});